es:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cowdrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Coudrai in Seine-Maritime, France, or Coudray in Eure, France, or from Cowdray or Cowdry in Sussex, England. The latter was probably named after one of the places in France. All are named with Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’ (a collective noun from <i>coudre</i> ‘hazelnut tree’, Late Latin <i>colurus</i>, a metathesized form of classical Latin <i>corylus</i>, from Greek <i>korylos</i>). Alternatively, but less likely, a topographic name from Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’, adopted into English, denoting someone who lived near a hazel copse."],"variants":[{"name":"Cowdery","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Cowdrey  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas de Cowdrey was born in 1420, in Essex, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Robert de Cowdrey and Mrs Robert de Cowdrey. He had at least 1 son with Jane Marie Edwards. He died in 1499, in Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 79."},"et":{"14